ops.insert: Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions

textDelta: What is the Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions? The Moscow Treaty, formally called the Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions, is a bilateral agreement between United States and the Russian Federation. It was signed on December 8, 1987, and entered into force on June 5, 1991. The Moscow Treaty is a follow-up to the Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty (INF Treaty), which was signed by U.S. President Ronald Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev in 1987. The INF Treaty eliminated all nuclear and conventional ground-launched ballistic and cruise missiles with ranges of 500 to 5,500 kilometers

What does the Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions accomplish? The Moscow Treaty on Strategic Offensive Reductions (SORT), signed by Presidents Obama and Medvedev in April 2010, commits both countries to reduce their deployed strategic warheads to 1,550 each, and 700 launchers to 800 each. The treaty does not, however, include limits on non-deployed strategic warheads and launchers. The treaty is of historic significance. It is the first arms control agreement to reduce nuclear weapons since 1991, when START I expired.
